      <!-- WHAT WE MAKE -->
      <section id="how-it-works">
        <h2>What we are building</h2>
        <div class="cols">
          <div>
            <strong>Instrumented memory layer</strong>
            <p>
              Lightweight clients wrap vector‑DB and key‑value stores used as agent memory.
              We log every write and read, plus which tools and actions follow each recall.
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>Plug into existing agents in minutes</li>
              <li>No change to prompts or business logic</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div>
            <strong>Attribution & detection engine</strong>
            <p>
              Our backend correlates unexpected behaviors with specific memory chunks and
              surfaces patterns that look like memory poisoning, persistent backdoors, or
              goal drift.
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>“This action happened because of memory M‑123”</li>
              <li>Detects long‑horizon zombie‑agent patterns</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div>
            <strong>Security control plane</strong>
            <p>
              A simple console gives security and platform teams visibility into their
              agents’ memories and lets them quarantine, mute, or roll back risky state
              without touching model weights.
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>One‑click quarantine & rollback</li>
              <li>Tenant‑ and agent‑level policies</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- WHY NOW -->
      <section>
        <h2>Why now</h2>
        <div class="cols">
          <div>
            <span class="tag"><span>☣</span> Zombie agents</span>
            <p>
              Enterprises are giving agents long‑term memory and access to real systems
              (email, CRM, billing).  
              Memory poisoning and persistent backdoors can turn those agents into
              “zombies” that quietly exfiltrate data or bypass policy.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <strong>Missing layer in the stack</strong>
            <p>
              Existing AI security tools focus on prompts, inputs, and permissions.
              Almost nobody is watching the long‑term memory that actually shapes
              agent behavior over days or weeks.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <strong>Our wedge</strong>
            <p>
              Membrane owns the link between memory and action.  
              We don’t replace observability or firewalls – we make them smarter by
              showing <em>which memories</em> are making your agents act strangely and
              giving you precise controls to neutralize them.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
